Pompeius adstrinxit: This was done in the lex Pompeia de vi et ambitu, passed in 52 Β.0., when Pompey was consul sine collega, ‘corrigendis moribus delectus' (Tac. Ann. III 28). The trial for ‘bribery' was limited to four days, three for the deposition of testimony, one for the speeches of counsel, the defendant being allowed three hours, the plaintiff two. Cf. Cic. Brut. 94, 324 lege Pompeia tribus horis ad dicendum datis de fin. IV 1 cum ego te hac nova lege videam eodem die accusatori res- pondere et tribus horis perorare Cass. Dio. XL 52 χρόνον τε τῷ διώκοντι δύο ὥρας, τῷ δὲ φεύγοντι τρεῖς διδόσθαι ἐκέλευσεν. Cp. Drumann, Ram. Gesclc. II 351 f. This law was, in the days of the younger Pliny, either no longer in vogue, or, what is more probable, origi- nally applicable only to cases ‘ de vi et ambitu.' Cf. Ep.
